*Ad Psychology Framework Breakdown*

This UGC prompt system is built on performance marketing psychology principles commonly used in paid acquisition campaigns.

The first layer focuses on the pattern interrupt. The initial three seconds determine whether a viewer continues watching or scrolls. Hooks must introduce curiosity, relatability, or a bold emotional trigger immediately.
The second layer emphasizes relatable problem articulation. Instead of directly selling a product, the script builds identification. Viewers must see themselves in the struggle being described.
The third layer introduces discovery. This makes the product feel found rather than sold, increasing trust and lowering resistance.
The fourth layer highlights solution clarity. The product must be positioned as simple, beginner-friendly, and directly beneficial.
The fifth layer provides emotional proof. Instead of unrealistic claims, the script focuses on feelings, transformation, or experience-based outcomes.
The final layer is the call-to-action. CTAs are structured as either soft recommendations or urgency-driven prompts depending on campaign objectives.
This layered structure ensures the content is persuasive while maintaining authenticity.
